Assignment 6: AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation¶

 

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help

Objective:¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms, and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Data Dictionary:¶

  1. Sl_No: Primary key of the records
  2. Customer Key: Customer identification number
  3. Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
  4. Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
  5. Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
  6. Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
  7. Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

'''
Input:
Pandas DataFrame

Output:
Displays DataFrame structure 
(columns, nulls and non nulls counts and percentage highlighing columns with most number of nulls)

Retunrs:
N/A
'''
def info(dataFrame):
    print(f"{dataFrame.shape[0]} Rows x {dataFrame.shape[1]} Columns")
    missing_values             = dataFrame.isna().sum()         # Get a series counting number of empty values for each column
    non_missing_values         = dataFrame.notnull().sum()      # Get a series counting number of non empty valuesfor each column 
    missing_values_percentage  = ((missing_values * 100)/(missing_values + non_missing_values)).astype(float)
    column_datatypes           = dataFrame.dtypes               # Get a series containing data types for each column 
    
    features      = [missing_values, non_missing_values, missing_values_percentage, column_datatypes]
    feature_names = ["Missing", "Non-Nulls","Missing %", "Type"]
    
    df = pd.concat(
        objs = features,
        axis = 1,
        keys = feature_names, 
        sort = True)
    
    cm = sns.light_palette("red", as_cmap=True)
    display(df.style.background_gradient(cmap=cm, subset=pd.IndexSlice[:, feature_names[1]]).format(formatter={(feature_names[2]): "{:.2f}%"}))

Check for Duplicate Customer Records¶

  • Each customer is identified by a unique primary key. it is expected that we have one record for each customer. This is because saying that a customer have 3 credits and also saying that the same customer has 3 credit cards is contradicting and causes confusion when having to classifiy this particular customer. Records of this kind are assumed to be error entries. In this section we look for those kind of customers and remove all of them as keeping one of them would be gambling since we dont have any reason to justify the choice.
  • In the exploration below we see these duplicate customers (in green) appearing on opposite sides of the charts for each pairplot,these customers with the same ids would have significantly different euclidean distances to other datapoints making the same customer appear on the different clusters.

'''
Input:
Outliers_Df : A filtered dataframe that contains only outliers.
Labeled_Df  : A dataframe to mark the outliers on
Features    : A list of two features to treat outliers for.

Results:
plots a scatter plot with outliers labeled.
returns Labeled_Df with outliers labeled.

Required:
Labeled_Df must have a column named 'labels' which telle if a row is an ourlier or not.
'''
def MarkOutliers(Outliers_Df, Labeled_Df, Features, ShowPlot = True):
    outlier_customers_ids = Outliers_Df[CUSTOMER_PRIMARY_KEY].to_list()

    def SetOutlierLabel(x):
        if x[CUSTOMER_PRIMARY_KEY] in outlier_customers_ids:
           x['labels'] = 'Outlier'
        return x

    Labeled_Df = Labeled_Df.apply(SetOutlierLabel, axis=1)
    
    if ShowPlot:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))
        ax = sns.scatterplot(data=Labeled_Df, x=Features["x"], y=Features["y"], hue='labels', palette=outliers_pallete, ax=ax)
        ax.set(title=f'Outlier Treatment for {Features["x"]} v.s. {Features["y"]}')
        ax.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
        plt.show()
    
    return Labeled_Df

'''
Plot a scatter plot for the given features and dataframe.
'''
def ScatterPlotBeforeOutlierTreatment(Df, Features):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10))
    ax = sns.scatterplot(data=Df, x=Features["x"], y=Features["y"], palette=outliers_pallete, ax=ax)
    ax.set(title=f'{Features["x"]} v.s. {Features["y"]}')
    plt.show()
    
'''
Input:
given a outlier constrains ins the form:
Outlier_Constrains = [
    [
        labeled_df['Avg_Credit_Limit'] >= 100000,
        labeled_df['Total_Credit_Cards'] >= 2,
        labeled_df['Total_Credit_Cards'] <= 5,
    ],
    [
        labeled_df['Avg_Credit_Limit'] >= 50000,
        labeled_df['Total_Credit_Cards'] < 4
    ]
]

Output:
it filters out all the outliers in that constraint list and returns 
a dataframe containing those outliers.
'''
def GetOutlierSDataFrame(df, outlier_constraints):
    outlier_constraint_dfs = []
    for constraint_set in outlier_constraints:
        temp_df = df.copy()
        for constrain in constraint_set:
            temp_df = temp_df[constrain]
        outlier_constraint_dfs.append(temp_df)
    return pd.concat(outlier_constraint_dfs,axis=0)

General Observations:¶

  • Customers who own more credit cards have a higher credit limit
  • Customers with a higher credit limit and a higher number of credit cards tend to make visit the bank online and make less phone calls to the bank.

clusters = range(1, 9)
meanDistortions = []
k_means_data_scaled_subset = k_means_data_scaled.iloc[:,1:7].copy()
for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(k_means_data_scaled_subset)
    prediction = model.predict(k_means_data_scaled_subset)
    distortion = (
        sum(
            np.min(cdist(k_means_data_scaled_subset, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1)
        )
        / k_means_data_scaled_subset.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)

K-Means Customer Segments:¶

  • Group 0 Customers:
    • These customers have average credit limit between 0 and 75000
    • Own about 4 to 7 credit cards
    • And tend to make about 2 to 5 physical visits to the bank and 0 to 2 visits online per year. They have the highest number of physical visits comparedto all goups.
    • And make about 0 to 4 calls to the bank per year.
  • Group 1 Customers:
    • These customers have the lowest average credit limit that is between 0 and 25000
    • They also own a fewer number of credit cards (1-4) compared to the first group.
    • These customers tend to make less number of physical visits (1-2) to the banks and more online visits 2-5 compared to the first group.
    • These customers also tend to make the highest number of calls to the bank compared to all other groups.
  • Group 2 Customers:
    • These customers have the highest credit limit (100k to 200k), own more credit cards (7-10) and have the highest number of online visits compared to all groups.
    • They also make less physical visits and phone calls to the bank compared to all groups.

class MODEL_ATTR():
    LINKAGE_MATRIX       = 'Linkage Matrix' 
    CORROLATION_DISTANCE = 'Corrolation Distance'
    COPHENETIC_DISTANCE  = 'Cophenetic Distance'
In [62]:
def BuildAndGetCluster(transformed_df, linkage_metric, linkage_method):
    clustering_linkage_matrix = linkage(
        y      = transformed_df,
        metric = linkage_metric,
        method = linkage_method)
    
    corr_dist, coph_dists = cophenet(clustering_linkage_matrix , pdist(transformed_df))
    
    return {
        MODEL_ATTR.LINKAGE_MATRIX       : clustering_linkage_matrix,
        MODEL_ATTR.CORROLATION_DISTANCE : corr_dist,
        MODEL_ATTR.COPHENETIC_DISTANCE  : coph_dists
    }
In [63]:
def ShowCorrolationScores(measurement):
    scores     = pd.DataFrame(index=evaluation_metrics, columns=linkage_methods)
    top_score  = 0
    best_model = ""
    print(measurement)
    for evaluation_metric in evaluation_metrics:
        for linkage_method in linkage_methods:
            try:
                scores.at[evaluation_metric, linkage_method] = BuildAndGetCluster(
                    transformed_df = hierarchical_clust_data_scaled.iloc[:,1:7],
                    linkage_metric = evaluation_metric,
                    linkage_method = linkage_method)[measurement]

                if scores.at[evaluation_metric, linkage_method] > top_score:
                    top_score  = scores.at[evaluation_metric, linkage_method]
                    best_model = f"Best Model ({evaluation_metric} X {linkage_method}) with Score : {top_score}"

            except:
                scores.at[evaluation_metric, linkage_method] = -1

    print(best_model)
    scores.fillna(-1, inplace=True)
    return scores

    • And make about 0 to 4 calls to the bank per year.
  • Group 2 Customers:
    • These customers have the lowest average credit limit that is between 0 and 25000
    • They also own a fewer number of credit cards (1-4) compared to the first group.
    • These customers tend to make less number of physical visits (1-2) to the banks and more online visits 2-5 compared to the first group.
    • These customers also tend to make the highest number of calls to the bank compared to all other groups.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

  • There is mainly 3 group of customers.
  • Customers who own more credit cards have a higher credit limit
  • Customers with a higher credit limit and a higher number of credit cards tend to make visit the bank online and make less phone calls to the bank.

From both K-Means and Hierachichal models we observe that:¶

  • Group 0 Customers:
    • These customers have average credit limit between 0 and 75000
    • Own about 4 to 7 credit cards
    • And tend to make about 2 to 5 physical visits to the bank and 0 to 2 visits online per year. They have the highest number of physical visits comparedto all goups.
    • And make about 0 to 4 calls to the bank per year.
  • Group 1 Customers:
    • These customers have the lowest average credit limit that is between 0 and 25000
    • They also own a fewer number of credit cards (1-4) compared to the first group.
    • These customers tend to make less number of physical visits (1-2) to the banks and more online visits 2-5 compared to the first group.
    • These customers also tend to make the highest number of calls to the bank compared to all other groups.
  • Group 2 Customers:
    • These customers have the highest credit limit (100k to 200k), own more credit cards (7-10) and have the highest number of online visits compared to all groups.
    • They also make less physical visits and phone calls to the bank compared to all groups.
